commitmsg:
getinfo.cgi works for type information.

I really need to finish rewriting the database :-(
Fix some search types and trees not named 'mozilla-central.'
Reorder steps so things work from a clean build.
Store blobs and reuse them for HTML generation.
Linkify references again and remove the dependency on the database.
Clean up HTMLification, pt. 4: move HTML generation to the base.
Clean up HTMLification, pt. 3: don't require at newlines.
Clean up HTMLification, pt. 2: Tokenization changes
Clean up HTMLification, pt. 1: generic sidebar generation.
Multiprocessing sucks. Global objects are much more performant.

Glue post-processing in with xref generation.

The medium-term goals are to implode xref-scripts and to switch
HTMLification over to not using the SQL database but the big ball of
data.

Rework the build setup slightly for some more generic stuff.

The next major batch will come when I rearchitect how run-dxr.py works.

Changes related to references.

Note that reference linkifying is currently disabled since it is soooo
slow.

Make variable references actually work.

And things in macros really suck.
Build a sidebar with the new database model.
Move to the indexer plugin from libindex.

Database modifications. Now HTML generation works again.

Clicky things and searchy things still don't work.
More database modifications. Warning: this breaks HTML generation

Database redesign, part 1.

Try to avoid updating to this changeset in particular, later changesets
are better.
More changes to the clang parser. Should stop segfaulting, too.
Add implementation hierarchy.
Add more indexing.
Apparently, I don't remember how bash quoting works.
A partially-working clang dumping utility.

Separate out the build system from the rest of dxr.

--HG--
rename : dxr_data.py => www/dxr_data.py
Wrong mozconfig. This shold work better.

Make www setup easier. And update the README a bit.

--HG--

Merge pull request #24 from cleeland/issue22

Fix for issue #22
Update docs to reflect requirement for sqlite 3.7+ due to fts4 usage. Fixes issue #22.
Fix issue #21.

www: quote properly search terms in FTS queries

'-' characters in an FTS MATCH are also part of the syntax,
and MATCH 'foo-bar' (get all matches with "foo" but not "bar")
is distinct from MATCH '"foo-bar"' (get all matches with
"foo-bar").

So, make sure search terms as introduced in the search box are
quoted individually in FTS queries.

www: enable search on click within strings in code

Likewise to comments, clicking on words within strings will initiate
a search for that term.

www: enable search on click for code comments

Now clicking on a word in a code comment will start a search for that
term in the same tab.
www: Handle nonexistent reference IDs more gracefully

www: strip leading/trailing whitespaces before splitting search terms

This fixes an exception if the search term contains those characters,
as it was leading to a malformed NEAR usage in FTS queries.

dxr: optionally display the type list

The left hand list in the code view is now optionally displayed,
with a small -/+ button above to toggle visibility. Indexing
plugins may choose to collapse the type list for a generated
html file by default or not.

www: improve case insensitivity in sidebar results

Some direct (case sensitive) string matching was being used
for the results, have it done on normalized strings.

www: Redirect to files and type/function definitions on exact matches

If the string being searched matches exactly with a filename or
type/function definition, redirect directly there, the HTML files
will show a hint box to let the user do the search if it was really
meant.

www: prepare for search query redirections

if there's a "string" parameter in the GET variables when
displaying a generated HTML file, it will be taken as a hint
that the url is being displayed due to a search that provided
it as a direct result, so a box will be shown letting the user
get the search results themselves.

dxr: Fix link hrefs when other tags apply

The HTML generator was tripping up if a link applied to
an offset that was added previously some HTML tags, so
use the original string in order to create the link href.

www: Don't fail fetching text from generated files

Do not raise an exception if a query happened to hit a
generated and deleted file which couldn't make it to
the FTS table. Whether those files have a presence in
the DB or not is still debatable.

dxr: ensure sidebar tuples get the scope name

a sqlite3.Row isn't quite a dict, so the "'sname' in df" check
was spuriously returning false.

dxr: Store extents for types/functions/variables

Those were previously just stored in memory for HTML generation,
keep that data stored in the database too for the link generation
phase.

dxr: Handle empty extents more gracefully

Don't raise an exception if a link tuple has no extents,
just don't add the link.

clang: canonicalize class declarations straight away

The clang plugin used to generate distinct "type" entries in the
csv files for declarations like:

class FooBar;

And the indexer plugin would normalize those to point to the
real definition of the class. This step is now done directly
in the clang plugin, as it's less guess work and the data can
make it directly to the database.

update.sh: specify configuration file to dxr-index.py

This is so both are guaranteed to fetch the settings from the
same place.

www: bound full text search terms to be nearby

NEAR is now used in the match string, so matching looks for
the multiple search terms confined within a range, this is
likely to provide more meaningful resources than looking for
the search terms throughout the whole content.

www: Update frontend to schema change

All queries upon *loc fields have been updated to the new schema.

dxr: Perform more operations directly against the DB

The indexing phase has been refurbished so more data hits directly
the database and less is retained in memory. The clang plugin has
changed too to adapt to this, resulting in overall lower times for
indexing (from ~3h30m to ~40m) and lower memory usage (peaking at
25% of the original one)

The database schema had to change too in order to allow for perfomant
queries as well for HTML generation, all *loc fields have been
replaced by file_id/line/col triplets, with a foreign key on the
files table, so searching for a given file doesn't result in a full
table scan. With these changes, dxr-index.py is able to generate an
average of 37 HTML files per second.
update.sh: Ensure the config file envvar isn't overwritten

www: enable middle clicking on the code to start a new search

The left button still shows the info popup on the token clicked, whereas
middle clicking would let it open a new tab/window with the token search
results.

fts: use case-insensitive matching

This is for parity with MXR, so search results are similar

dxr-index: Use dxrCodeTokenizer for code tokenization

All inserted text in the fts table will use this tokenizer. The

Add FTS4 code-friendlier tokenizer

This tokenizer will provide tokens for both the joined and
split forms of CamelCase and underscore_separated strings,
enabling searches of full function/class names, or parts of
these. This results in more coherent results from code searches.

The module loading is a bit convoluted, and could be simplified
in the future if python sqlite bindings enabled extension loading.
It currently requires a module function to be called through ctypes,
and a call to a custom sqlite function to enable the tokenizer
for the calling handle.

since the request is issued to when the content is shown is
measured
www,search: Add timing measurements about content generation

www,search: Use FTS4 sqlite table for searches

the FTS table is accessed either through using the MATCH operator,
or through the rowid. All usage of the .txt files has been removed.

dxr-index: Use FTS4 sqlite table to store searchable contents

This replaces both file_index.txt and file_list.txt files, which
aren't generated anymore. As FTS lookups are most performant on
MATCH or on rowid matching, an additional files table is created
to improve performance on path-based searches.

Use "python" instead of "python2" in Python shebangs

On most systems, /usr/bin/python is Python 2.  On some systems, there
is a symlink from /usr/bin/python2 to Python 2, but not on all.

(There are also systems, like Arch Linux, that point
/usr/bin/python to Python 3.  They believe the correct thing for
Python 2 software to do is to use /usr/bin/python and require
Arch end users to fix these paths manually.  See
  http://www.mail-archive.com/arch-general@archlinux.org/msg23313.html
)

Print out current on parse error when loading indexer output

source tree and attempted to load it, causing an exception other

Fix formating of incremental search results when the matching source code contains a dollar sign. Consider a source file that contains this line: a = '$'; When the template is formatted this will boil down to a call like "...{{line}}...".replace( new RegExp("\\{\\{line\\}\\}", "g"), "a = '$';"); The desired result is: "...a = '$';..." Instead the $' is treated as a a replacement pattern (see https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/replace#Specifying_a_string_as_a_parameter) so the result ends up being the malformed: "...a = '...;..." To fix this all dollar signs in the replacement string should be doubled to escape them before passing to String.replace.

Move some files around in preparation for turning the Python parts into a legitimate package. (Tests should fail.)

The dxr folder is going to form the core of an installable package. search.py, query.py, and utils.py never change; they just get copied on build. Thus, those can live in the installed package, and the build can just be a config file and .htaccess. To serve, run dxr-serve.py --config=/my/build/dir. We can explain that in the last 2 lines output from dxr-build, much as we currently do with test-server. For WSGI, we can pass in the path to the config file in an env var.

Because this reduces repetition, it makes dev easier: we can just edit the single, installed (with python setup.py develop) version of the server, and git will pick it upno more having to edit an untracked build artifact. More standard installation and project layout probably won't hurt our community adoption, either.

Note that the package won't encompass the entire project, as there's no nice way to make setup.py build trilite and the clang plugins (that I know of).

dxr-build: allow specifying tree build order

Add support for an optional |order| parameter tp tree configs; it should be
an integer, with smaller values being built first.  Trees with unspecified
order will be built after those with specified order, in sorted by tree
name.

dxr-build: add ignore patterns involving the whole path

This adds support for ignore_patterns that take the whole path into
account.  Any ignore patterns that start with "/" will be matched against
the whole path relative to the root of the source tree, instead of just the
leaf name of the item.

Note that this doesn't do the right thing - it will happily match sub-
directories with a single "*".

Add profiling ability for SQL queries.

Appending "&explain=true" to the end of the URL of any query will run
the query as normal but not return the results to the browser.
Instead it will report the results of "EXPLAIN QUERY PLAN" for every
SQL statement that is run along with the time that each statement took.

This can be useful in diagnosing slow queries and figuring out how to
speed them up.

Merge pull request #37 from abbeyj/testing

Fix for "Jump to definition" sometimes jumping to a declaration instead.

Fix for "Jump to definition" sometimes jumping to a declaration instead.
Now "function" is emitted to the .csv only for function definitions, not
declarations.  Declarations will get a "decldef" if a definition is
available elsewhere in the translation unit.

Having multiple "function" entries for a single function would cause
the UNION in indexer.py:update_refs to return more than one row
(one from functions and one from decldef).  If the one from decldef
won then "Jump to definition" worked.  If the one from functions won
then you'd be taken to the declaration instead.  SQLite seems to
break this tie based on the numeric value of the ID so the behavior
was somewhat nondeterministic when minor changes were made to the
source code.
